\section{Reading top-level tutorial metadata}

The front matter must be a small YAML mapping.  We keep the schema narrow
so mistakes fail fast and tutorial authors can see exactly what the file
is expected to provide.

<<functions>>=
def front_matter_mapping(front_matter: str) -> dict:
    """Return the parsed YAML mapping for one tutorial front matter block."""

    payload = yaml.safe_load(front_matter) or {}
    if not isinstance(payload, dict):
        raise ValueError("Tutorial front matter must be a YAML mapping.")
    return payload
@


\section{Parsing one tutorial text}

The parser itself should not care whether the Markdown came from a local
file, a downloaded URL, or a future in-memory source.  Keeping the text
parser separate lets the installer validate raw tutorial content without
duplicating any schema checks.

<<functions>>=
def parse_tutorial_text(
    text: str,
    *,
    source_path: str | Path | None = None,
) -> Tutorial:
    """Parse one Markdown tutorial text into a [[Tutorial]]."""

    front_matter, body = split_yaml_front_matter(text)
    metadata = front_matter_mapping(front_matter)
    reject_unknown_keys(metadata, {"id", "title", "summary"}, "Tutorial")

    steps = tuple(
        build_tutorial_step(title, section_body)
        for title, section_body in split_step_sections(body)
    )
    return Tutorial(
        id=require_string(metadata, "id", "Tutorial"),
        title=require_string(metadata, "title", "Tutorial"),
        summary=require_string(metadata, "summary", "Tutorial"),
        steps=steps,
        source_path=None if source_path is None else str(source_path),
        source_digest=build_source_digest(text),
    )
