\section{Building one tutorial step}

Once the optional metadata block is separated from the Markdown body, step
construction still has four distinct concerns.  We first extract the authored
metadata and student-facing instructions, then derive the interaction shape,
then reject unsupported combinations, and only after that build the final
[[TutorialStep]].

That separation matters because the interaction schema is intentionally small:
shell is the default, [[edit_file]] still selects editor steps, and authored
questions add [[kind]], [[options]], and [[answers]].  Keeping the phases
visible makes it easier to see where we interpret that schema and where we
merely copy validated values into the model.

The recorded-text checks are slightly richer.  Tutorials may still use a
simple YAML list of strings, but each item can also be a small mapping with
an explicit match mode.  That keeps common cases short while leaving room
for regular expressions when a step genuinely needs them.

<<functions>>=
def build_tutorial_step(title: str, section_body: str) -> TutorialStep:
    """Build one tutorial step from a parsed Markdown section."""

    <<extract step metadata and instructions>>
    <<derive the interaction shape>>
    <<reject invalid step shapes>>
    <<construct the tutorial step>>
@

The first phase separates student-facing instructions from authored control
metadata and rejects keys the runtime does not understand.  Doing that work up
front keeps later phases about meaning rather than about defensive bookkeeping.

<<extract step metadata and instructions>>=
metadata, instructions = step_metadata_and_instructions(section_body)
reject_unknown_keys(
    metadata,
    {
        "answers",
        "check_command",
        "edit_file",
        "hint",
        "kind",
        "options",
        "required_patterns",
    },
    f"Step {title!r}",
)
if not instructions:
    raise ValueError(f"Step {title!r} must contain instructions.")
@

Next we derive the small interaction schema from the raw metadata.  This keeps
all interpretation of [[kind]], [[options]], and [[answers]] in one place
before we ask whether the combination is valid.

<<derive the interaction shape>>=
kind = optional_string(metadata.get("kind"), f"Step {title!r} kind")
has_options = "options" in metadata
has_answers = "answers" in metadata
options = option_tuple(metadata.get("options"), f"Step {title!r} options")
answers = step_answers(metadata, title, kind)
edit_file = optional_string(
    metadata.get("edit_file"),
    f"Step {title!r} edit_file",
)
@

Shape validation stays separate so the schema rules read as one coherent gate:
editor steps, shell steps, and authored questions each allow different pieces
of metadata, and we reject impossible combinations before constructing the
model object.

<<reject invalid step shapes>>=
validate_step_shape(
    title,
    kind=kind,
    has_options=has_options,
    has_answers=has_answers,
    options=options,
    answers=answers,
    edit_file=edit_file,
)
@

Once the metadata has passed those checks, construction really is a direct
mapping into [[TutorialStep]].  Keeping that final phase small makes it clear
that the earlier chunks already did the interpretive work.

<<construct the tutorial step>>=
return TutorialStep(
    title=title,
    instructions=instructions,
    kind=kind,
    options=options,
    answers=answers,
    required_patterns=text_match_tuple(
        metadata.get("required_patterns"),
        f"Step {title!r} required_patterns",
    ),
    check_command=optional_string(
        metadata.get("check_command"),
        f"Step {title!r} check_command",
    ),
    hint=optional_string(metadata.get("hint"), f"Step {title!r} hint"),
